[src:conjugate-gradient-method/conjugate-gradient-method] The above algorithm gives the most straightforward explanation of the conjugate gradient method.
[src:conjugate-gradient-method/conjugate-gradient-method] Seemingly, the algorithm as stated requires storage of all previous searching directions and residue vectors, as well as many matrix–vector multiplications, and thus can be computationally expensive.
[src:conjugate-gradient-method/conjugate-gradient-method] However, a closer analysis of the algorithm shows that $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf {r} _{j}$ , i.e. $\mathbf {r} _{i}^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {r} _{j}=0$ , for $i\neq j$ .
[src:conjugate-gradient-method/conjugate-gradient-method] Therefore, $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ can be regarded as the projection of $\mathbf {x}$ on the Krylov subspace.
[src:conjugate-gradient-method/conjugate-gradient-method] The algorithm is detailed below for solving $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ where $\mathbf {A}$ is a real, symmetric, positive-definite matrix.
